node.text: What makes Aldabra Atoll so special? Apart from the healthy and vibrant inshore marine environment with abundant sharks, unlogged mangrove forests and a pristine lagoon the size of Manhattan? Well this remote Seychelles atoll has a way of getting under your skin and saturates your heart and soul. Those of us fortunate enough to set foot on and explores its shores are spoilt for life ! Some of you asked what the black is in the upper part of the first photo? I was inside a underwater cavern looking out, the black is part of the cave entrance overhang. @sif_seychelles #seychelles #aldabra #wilderness #ocean #island #indianocean

node.text:
The best camera/lens combination is often simply the one you are holding in your hands!

I was walking through coastal forest on the tiny Seychelles island of Cousine when a white term began to hover inches from my face and tried to land on my head. Unfortunately I was on my way to go diving, so in addition to wearing a wetsuit and clutching my fins in my teeth I was holding my heavy/bulky underwater camera setup. With no other option than use the gear in my hands, I raised my underwater rig to my eye, framed as best i could and hit the shutter. 

I think this the only terrestrial photograph that I have ever shot on assignment for @natgeo with a underwater camera. 

Unpublished photograph from my 2015 @natgeo story on island restoration in Seychelles. 

#seychelles #islandlife #birdsofinstagram #seabirds

node.text: Aldabra atoll is one of the most magical places on our planet! I have been fortunate to have spent many months based at the @sif_seychelles Aldabra research station, which celebrates its 50th anniversary this month. My time on the atoll resulted in a feature story for @natgeo and a book for @saveourseasfoundation In this gallery I want to share some previously unpublished images from this island wilderness. Let me know which one is your favorite. #seychelles #indianocean #sharks #tortoises

node.text: Bryde’s whales have been both a blessing and a curse for me on the sardine run. On the one hand they make for action packed photographs, not afraid to lunge feed on sardines just a few meters away from me. The downside is that they can finish off and swallow a bus sized baitball of fish in a matter of minutes, quickly putting an end to my photographic ambitions that day. #sardinerun #southafrica #ocean #whales

node.text: Cape Gannets rarely end up on a shark’s menu, but during South Africa’s sardine run, both compete intensely for the same rich silvery resource, sardines! Only the first and last photographs in this gallery have seen the light of day in publications or online. The other images  did not quite come together the way I wished and languished on hard drives until now. However they nonetheless help to tell the story and give a broader visual perspective of the setting and the behavior. #sardinerun #sharks #southafrica #ocean #seabirds

node.text:
In South Africa July is synonymous with the sardine run, a spectacular marine wildlife event with few equals. This year I am not chasing these silvery fish and the predators that feast upon them. Instead I am researching and preparing for two new and challenging @natgeo / @insidenatgeo assignments. 

As exciting as these new stories are, a few hours ago FOMO hit hard and I consoled myself by looking through some of my images from sardine runs of past years. 

Today I want to share some photographs of long beaked common dolphins, the true architects of the sardine run. They are the only predator that hunts cooperatively and is fast enough to physically control and manipulated the movement of the sardines. Working together the dolphins carve off smaller, more manageable groups of fish off the many miles long main shoal. They then herd them toward the surface and create bait balls, the holy grail for all those who chose to pit themselves again the elements to document one of the greatest, but also one most difficult and unpredictable natural history events in the world. 

#southafrica #sardinerun #ocean #underwater #underwaterphotography #diving #wildcoast #adventure #wildlifephotography #dolphins #sardines #fomo #onassignment #baitball

node.text:
Antarctica and the remote islands of the Southern Ocean are some of my favorite wild places on our planet. I am therefore delighted to announce that I will be partnering with @coexistprojects as an ambassador to help raise some critical funding for conservation research on penguins and other Antarctic predators. 

What I love about Co-Exist is that, not only do they support some of my favorite grassroots marine conservation organizations, but that through your purchases you can decide which marine animal you want to help protect. 

When I see the enthusiasm and dedication with which Sarah and her colleagues built CO-EXIST, I am comforted knowing that the next generation of marine conservation champions is not only passionate but also immensely capable.

Please, give my friends @coexistprojects a follow and see how you can #helpsaveourseas

All photographs made on expedition for the Save our Seas Foundation

node.text: A gray whale calf surfaces to breathe with its much larger mother floating right below. The water in Baja California's San Ignacio lagoon is usually a murky green and photographing the gray whales that come here to mate and give birth, underwater is usually very tricky. I spent almost a month working this lagoon for the 2017 @natgeo magazine story ‘Baja’s Ocean Stewards’ and only for a short, but very memorable 45 minutes I hit the jackpot. The tide pushed in beautiful clear blue water and I had more curious whales around the boat then I knew what to do with. @maresmexicanos. #Baja #mexico #whales #conservation #ocean #nature #wildlifephotography #underwater

node.text: World Albatross Day always reminds of my time spent on remote islands in the Southern Ocean. Turn on the sound for this one !!! You will thank me :-) // One of my highlights of trekking across sub-Antarctic Marion Island in 2017 was photographing the “dancing grounds” of the wandering albatross, one of the largest flying birds in the world. In late afternoon sub-adults gather in small groups on the grassy coastal plain and break out into the species’ ritual dance, designed to help them size up prospective partners. With a elegant repertoire of bowing and sky-calling these performances might appear ballet-like, but surprisingly they sound like a bunch of donkeys. On assignment for @NatGeo in collaboration with @environmentza and the South African National Antarctic Program. Video shot by my long suffering assistant (and seabird biologist and filmmaker) @ottowhitehead Please give him a follow for more great videos.

node.text: Giraffes can be real boneheads! They seek out carcasses of a variety of species and chew on the bones left behind. This phenomenon is called osteophagia and translates into “feeding on bone”. They do extract calcium, but the bones are never swallowed and the minerals just supplement the giraffe’s regular diet of Acacia leaves and flowers. Shot on assignment for @natgeo working with @tswalufoundation
